## Did You Know?

- If you ingested your data using ArcGIS Pro or ArcGIS Online, you can add additional datasets using the ArcGIS Living Atlas.
- In ArcGIS Online, you can also drag and drop your data file directly onto the map, which will add it to your content under **My Content**.
- In QGIS, you can add publicly hosted data on ArcGIS Online through the ArcGIS REST Server: https://docs.qgis.org/3.44/en/docs/user_manual/managing_data_source/opening_data.html
- In the Contents pane (ArcGIS) or Layers List (QGIS), polygon layers toward the top will obscure layers listed beneath. You can drag and drop polygon layers to the bottom of the list so they do not cover your other data.

## Troubleshooting

- **Coordinate System and Projection Errors**
  - Missing or Wrong CRS: If you load tabular data (such as a CSV with XY coordinates) and points do not plot in the correct location or fail to draw, your CRS is likely mismatched. Confirm the data's coordinate system and ensure your map uses the same system.

- **Corrupt Geometry**
  - Check Geometry: Some features may have corrupt, null, or looping geometries.
  - The Fix:
    - ArcGIS Online: There is no native tool to fix corrupt geometry. Download the data and repair it manually or in ArcGIS Pro.
    - ArcGIS Pro: Run the **Check Geometry** tool, then run **Repair Geometry** to fix invalid features.
    - QGIS: Run the **Fix Geometries** tool found in **Processing > Toolbox**.

- **Attribute Table Errors ("Could Not Load Data")**
  - Failed to load rows: If the map draws features but the attribute table fails to open, there may be schema mismatches or bad spatial indexes.
  - The Fix:
    - ArcGIS Online: Download the data and review attribute table errors. Check for null values or unsupported characters.
    - ArcGIS Pro: Recalculate thea new File Geodatabase.
    - QGIS:
      - Run **Create Spatial Index** if you receive a "No Spatial Index" error.
      - For schema issues, install and run the **Table Structure Compare** plugin.

